Erasistratus (fl. 280 sc.) is said to have been the first to use the distinctive epithet. The word ἀρτηρία (connected with ἀείρω, ἀορτήρ· properly means ‘suited for suspending', and is fitly used for that from which the lungs and other vitel parts are suspended, and by which they are held up when the animal is opened after death: hence Sophocles calls it πνεύμονος ἀρτηρίας Trauli. 1054 ‘suspendere of the lungs ' (the plural is used for the two bronchial tubes). In like manner the tube or cord from which the heart is suspended is called ἆορτη, cf. Arist. H. A.
